  "Idea": "This paper proposes the design and implementation of PeerBench, a novel benchmark framework specifically engineered to evaluate both closed- and open-source large language models (LLMs) in their ability to perform scientific peer review critique tasks using the ReviewCritique dataset. Unlike conventional benchmarks that prioritize task completion accuracy, PeerBench emphasizes two underexplored yet vital dimensions: (1) reasoning fidelity—the degree to which a model's justification structure mirrors that of expert human reviewers in terms of logical coherence, evidence grounding, and critique taxonomy alignment; and (2) calibration robustness—the alignment between a model’s confidence (e.g., logit entropy, self-assessed certainty) and its actual correctness in identifying valid weaknesses or strengths in scientific papers. PeerBench operationalizes these through a multi-tiered evaluation protocol grounded in Evidence-Centered Benchmark Design (ECBD), ensuring each component is justified by explicit claims about targeted capabilities. The framework includes four core modules: (a) Critique Consistency Scoring, which uses semantic similarity and argument mining techniques to compare model-generated critiques against human-written ones in the ReviewCritique dataset, normalized across subfields and paper quality strata; (b) Reasoning Trajectory Analysis, which decomposes model outputs into premise-evidence-conclusion chains and evaluates them via fine-grained rubrics derived from NLP peer review guidelines; (c) Confidence-Calibration Testing, where models are prompted to assign confidence scores to individual critique assertions, later evaluated using Expected Calibration Error (ECE) and Brier scores across high- vs. low-agreement review cases; and (d) Rebuttal Resilience Assessment, measuring how well models update or defend their initial critiques when presented with author rebuttals—an adaptation of the after-rebuttal prediction task in Paper 1, but flipped